Ilon Mask is forced to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla
The US Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Ilon Musk settled their fraud dispute.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the channel, under the agreements reached Mask will have to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Mask to keep the post of the head of Tesla.
As noted, the founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative fine of $ 20 million.
A similar amount will be charged with Tesla.
At the same time, the money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
According to Forbes magazine, Ilon Musk is an American entrepreneur on the list of the 50 richest people on the planet.
He is the head of the SpaceX space corporation, the Neuralink neuroscience company and the Tesla electric vehicle developer, and also the co-founder of Paypal
The US Securities and Exchange Commission earlier sued Tesla's CEO Ilona Mask because of his message on Twitter about a possible buyout of the company.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy back all the shares on the exchange at a fixed price of $ 420.
The cost of the share was set at $ 420 allegedly "because of the significance of this number in the culture of marijuana," Bloomberg reported earlier, citing Stephen Paykin, co-director of the security department.
At the same time, Ilon Mask subsequently abandoned his plans to buy back shares.
Commenting on a lawsuit filed against him by the US Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman stated that he considered the charges of fraud unsubstantiated and added that he was very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
“Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts will prove that I didn’t break it in any way,” the businessman told CNBC.
In August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a class action lawsuit against Musk, complaining of financial losses incurred.
The plaintiffs claimed that the posts of the businessman brought them losses.
In particular, one of the shareholders said that the businessman’s tweets were misleading, which is why Tesla stock sellers were forced to buy securities at artificially high prices to cover their positions.
Also, other plaintiffs noted that careless statements by Ilon Mask led to sharp fluctuations in the course.
In September, Ilona Musk accused the head of research company Citron Research of fraud.
Meanwhile, if Musk could not settle his dispute with the US Securities and Exchange Commission, he would be in danger of being removed from management and even a prison.
About this, in particular, said the former CNBC chairman Harvey Pitt on CNBC.
Musk - "a good guy who can not manage a car company."
