In Indonesia after the earthquake, more than 100 prisoners escaped from prison
More than 100 prisoners escaped from prison in the Indonesian province of Central Sulawesi.
Escape became possible after two powerful earthquakes on an island of 7.2 and 7.4.
According to the newspaper The Jakarta Post, the incident occurred on September 28, when prisoners in the prison city of Palu demanded to release them in connection with tremors.
More than 340 prisoners staged a riot and set fire to the institution.
Police officers who arrived at the scene of the incident partially took control of the situation, but more than 100 people escaped from prison.
The building itself was severely damaged, and the guards could hardly keep the prisoners.
The number of earthquake and tsunami victims that occurred on the island of Sulawesi has increased to 832 people.
In this regard, it is still not possible to establish a transport link, electricity supply and communication with some areas of the island.
