Called the death of the universe
The universe will last about 140 billion years, which is ten times more than the age of the observed world, equal to about 13.8 billion years.
The study of the international team of scientists posted in the library of electronic preprints arXiv.org and sent for publication in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan, reports the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
Experts arrived at similar conclusions by observing about ten million galaxies using the HSC (Hyper Suprime-Cam) camera of the Subaru telescope.
Tracing the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which account for more than 95 percent of the energy-mass of the observed world, scientists, working within the standard cosmological model ΛCDM (Cold Cold Matter), estimated the rate of expansion of the Universe, which turned out to be slightly slower than previously thought.
In a press release, the Observatory of Subaru notes that the observations made it possible to obtain a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the Universe, and the recording of data from the European space telescope Planck specified the restrictions imposed on the parameters of ΛCDM.
In July, scientists modeled the possible destruction of the universe.
Three years earlier, their colleagues presented new arguments for the fact that the observed world would cease to exist in 22 billion years as a result of the Great Gap.
