Major Macedonian oppositionist refused to vote in referendum
In Macedonia, on Sunday, September 30, a referendum is held on an intergovernmental agreement with Greece on renaming the Republic of Macedonia.
Citizens are invited to answer one question: "Do you support EU and NATO membership by adopting an agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Hellenic Republic?"
Nevertheless, the leader of the leading opposition party, the Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization - the Democratic Party for the Macedonian National Unity (VMRO-DPNE), Christian Mitskosky, said that he would not vote in a referendum.
As the party’s spokesman, Naum Stoilkovsky, explained, Mitskosky decided to abstain from voting in order to express his disagreement with the treaty, which he considers "pernicious."
According to the press secretary, the current referendum resolves the issue of renaming the country and nothing more, while the strategic goal of the party is to achieve membership in NATO and the EU.
A week ago, the President of Macedonia, Gheorghe Ivanov, also refused to participate in the referendum on September 30.
He explained that he chose the name for the country 27 years ago in a referendum on independence. Macedonian leader considers renaming the country a negative factor.
“A new half-sovereign state is being created with a new name,” noted Ivanov.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav Republic - the Republic of Northern Macedonia - was signed by the foreign ministers of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a ceremony on the shore of Lake Prespa, which runs the border between the two countries.
This treaty should resolve the long-standing dispute over the name of the country, as well as Skopje, the path to NATO and the EU, reminds TASS.
